In the left part of the input grid, there are four different shaped yellow objects. To the right of those yellow objects, there's a single tile wide aqua vertical line. On the right section, there is a red vertical line with additional tiles on the left that makes it have uneven thickness along the entire line. The output grid has lots of changes, and specifically added a lot of yellow and aqua tiles in it, as well as moving some of the red tiles. Let's go through the specific changes from the input grid to the output grid section by section. In the left part of the input grid, the yellow objects have been changed to green objects, located in the exact same place and in the exact shape, just changed from yellow to green. Additionally, a yellow line of tiles has emerged to the right of all the now green objects, with each line being the same height as the total height of the now green objects. These potentially thick horizontal yellow stop at the vertical aqua line, and then the same thickness line proceeds to the right but as an aqua color line instead of yellow. The aqua colored horizontal lines then continue and effectively push only the red tiles that in their row to the right edge of the output grid. The rest of the rows in that line to the right of the vertical aqua line will be aqua. The transformation rule can be described as some type of beam that comes out of the yellow objects and gets color transformed by the aqua line, and then pushes the red objects to the right. Because this transformation rule has so many steps and is complex, let's see another training pair first before makin a hypothesis. Although we do likely have most of it already described and known.
thoughts.b: The input and output grids are again the same sizes. The input grid is mostly a black color background with a variety of different colored features in different sections of the input grid. In this case, the top part of the input grid, there are four different shaped yellow objects. Below those yellow objects there is a single tile wide aqua horizontal line. In the bottom section there is a vertical line with additional tiles on the top of it that makes it have uneven thickness along the entire line. The output grid looks very similar to the input grid but with many specific little changes, all consistent with the first training pair. Overall though, it is still effectively described as a beam that comes out of the yellow objects, gets transformed into the aqua color by the aqua line, and then pushes the red objects down to the bottom edge of the output grid. Thus our hypothesis is the following. The input grid will contain mostly black color background and three distinct sections. One section will have some number of different shaped yellow objects. Another section will have a vertical or horizontal single tile wide aqua line. The last section will contain a vertical or horizontal red line with uneven thickness throughout. In order to construct the output grid, we need to effectively add a beam that comes out of the yellow objects, gets color transformed by the aqua line, and then pushed the red objects in that beams path to the edge. For example, in this case, The aqua line is below the yellow objects, so we know the beam has to go down. We first start constructing the output grid by changing the yellow objects to green in their exact location and shapes as in the input grid. Then we add a beam of yellow tiles in the direction of the aqua line, with the same width as each of the now green objects. For each object, the yellow beam will continue to be yellow until it hits the aqua line, at which point the beam's thickness will not change, but the color will change to aqua. The beam continues to follow the same direction and then pushes any red tiles that are part of the uneven thickness red line in the same row or column until those red tiles hit the edge of the output grid. The output grid is the same size as the input grid, and the rest of the output grid stays the same, specifically the rest of the red tiles that are not in the path of a beam and thus have not been pushed to the edge are simply in the exact location as they were in the input grid.
